<CLR_EXEC>.llm_response: Counterfactual explanations help you understand how to change an input to achieve a different outcome from an AI model. They provide insights into what minimal changes to the input data would lead to a different prediction. For example, if an AI model predicts that a loan application will be rejected, a counterfactual explanation might show that increasing the applicant's income by a certain amount could result in an approval. This type of explanation is useful for understanding the decision boundaries of the model and for identifying actionable changes. In the context of images, counterfactuals might involve altering specific features of an image to change the classification outcome. This can be visualized by showing the original image alongside modified versions that lead to different predictions. The ISee Platform offers several explainers for generating counterfactual explanations. For multivariate tabular data, you can try the '/Tabular/NICE' explainer, which generates counterfactuals by exploiting information from a nearest instance to speed up the search process. Another option is the '/Tabular/DicePublic' explainer, which uses the ML model's training data as a baseline to generate diverse counterfactuals. These explainers can help you explore and understand the decision boundaries of your models effectively.
